{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563431"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T22:59:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T22:59:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16762"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16762"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.04,0.13,0.06,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9453"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112984"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9453"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16762"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95016"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4519"},{"type":"tags","id":"4638"},{"type":"tags","id":"4821"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22337"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45870"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46503"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112984"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her first antenatal visit at eight weeks gestation, confirmed by ultrasound. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy multivitamins. She has no known allergies. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. First trimester screening blood tests reveal a positive Rapid Plasma Reagin (RPR) test with a titre of 1:32 and a positive Treponema pallidum particle agglutination (TPPA) test. She has no previous history of positive serology.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Benzathine benzylpenicillin injection","Doxycycline tablets","Await confirmatory treponemal testing","Erythromycin tablets","Repeat RPR in four weeks"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has tested positive for syphilis during routine first trimester screening. The high RPR titre and positive TPPA without previous history indicates newly acquired infection. Congenital syphilis can cause severe complications including stillbirth, prematurity, and multisystem disease in the newborn. Therefore, prompt treatment is essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenzathine benzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E injection (specifically, benzathine benzylpenicillin 1.8g intramuscularly as a single dose) is the treatment of choice for syphilis in pregnancy. It effectively treats maternal infection and prevents transmission to the fetus. Treatment should be initiated as soon as possible after diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is a second-line treatment for patients with penicillin allergy. However, it does not reliably prevent congenital syphilis, and penicillin desensitisation should be considered in pregnant patients with penicillin allergy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeating the RPR\u003C/strong\u003E in four weeks without treatment would delay necessary therapy and increase the risk of fetal infection. While serial RPR titres are useful for monitoring treatment response, initial treatment should not be delayed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAwaiting confirmatory treponemal testing\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as both RPR and TPPA are already positive, confirming the diagnosis of syphilis. No further testing is required before initiating treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in pregnancy as it can cause permanent tooth discolouration and affect bone development in the fetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter treatment, the patient should have monthly RPR titres to monitor treatment response. Partner notification and treatment are essential to prevent reinfection. The infant will require close monitoring after birth.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Maternal syphilis should be treated with benzathine benzylpenicillin as soon as possible in pregnancy to prevent congenital syphilis.","All pregnant women should be screened for syphilis in the first trimester.","Partners of women with positive syphilis serology must be traced and treated to prevent reinfection."],"references":["Australasian Society for Infectious Diseases (ASID). Management of Perinatal Infections [Internet]. Melbourne: ASID; 2022 [cited 2024 Dec 1]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ASID-Management-of-Perinatal-Infections.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95016"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16762"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95016"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T20:39:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T20:39:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9453"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112984"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":fal